I see Colin in every Peter Lake scene, hear his voice--that's what it's all about for me--but he's only in the beginning and end of the very long book...I assume the movie has expanded on those parts of the book. I only picked up the book to read before the movie came out but am now scanning pages to get to the end--IDK how the movie will compare, though I'm in LOVE with Colin Farrell so I'm sure I'll like the movie, and understand it better, perhaps, for having read the book. He's a Dickensian writer for sure--was he paid by the word? How many similes and metaphors can you fit into a paragraph??? In this case, too many.

text: Truth be told, I just watched this movie for the first time today, half-expecting it to live up to my expectations that it would be a mediocre movie. However, I soon found myself liking this movie. True, to describe the plot of this movie is any reviewer's worst nightmare, and it's actually not as confusing as it sounds on paper. All of the actors were stunning (including Will Smith), and some of the special effects were absolutely amazing. This movie even had me crying at the end, and it's now considered one of my favorite romance movies. I find that it's rather underrated, but if you want to find out what it's all about, go ahead! You may like it or hate it in the end, but then again, the same can be said for all movies.

text: I read the novel in 1984 and it became my favorite work of fiction. For years, I wondered what ever happened to a film version. Martin Scorsese took a shot at it and decided against it. When the movie was released, I was disappointed. No character of Hardesty Maratta, no Jackson Mead - Master Bridge Builder of all time, were present in the film. The visual opportunities with the metaphor of the Bridge  of Light would have been spectacular. The magical sense of reality was mostly excised by writer/director Akiva Goldsman. The scene of Abby coming back to life left me in tears in the book. This movie scene, however, was devoid of any emotion. The screenplay was altered during writing as Goldsman's wife passed away, and he decided to do away with all story elements not directly connected to the love story between Peter Lake and Beverly Penn. A fine effort for what it was, but an enormous let down for me. Perhaps too ambitious of a film version of a rather sprawling novel.
